author: CodeWarrior-debug
postBody:
After a great visit to see family in Spain, it's time to begin the #100daysofcode !


Day 1 - 9% through ZTM's Complete Next.js Developer Course in 2023. LOVE the easier setup compared to create-react-app, the dead simple routing configuration, the image optimizations, and excited about Next.js's performance gains promised to come. Lightweight restaurant-finder app....COMING SOON.


After 4 hours of coding along with the tutorial, it was time for some leetcode problem solving. A uniqueChar problem example's cases were easily solved for, but upon submission the straighforward array iteration method resulted in a time limit exceeded error. Will retry after converting an array into a set that eliminates duplicates.


Looking forward to hitting it again tomorrow!
subtitle: 100 Days of Code - 1
title: So it begins...

subtitle: 100 Days of Code - 2
title: NextJS surge
author: CodeWarrior-debug
postBody:
Day 2 - %15 through Next.js course. Currently reviewing the options of client vs. server side rendering, static generation, incremental static regeneration, and the variety of techniques for delivering a complete page as fast as possible. Incremental static generation is highly favored by the instructor of this course for pages with changing data - interested in what others prefer?


To further hone the React skills, beginning to refactor into React a program written in Handlebars (using create-react-app, not Next.js). I was reluctant to start while taking the Next.js course because I want to avoid confusion between the two different styles of React. However, managing multiple projects simultaneously is typical in a professional career, so I am forging ahead. How many simultaneous coding projects do others juggle before it becomes unmanageable?



Like

Days 3&4 - 20% through Next.js course, reviewing getStaticPaths (for dynamically rendered pages) and fallback '404: Page Not Found' options. My overwhelming impression that Next.js is extremely thorough in its implementation keeps growing.


Had to pause 2x. Last week I had to wade through some sickness, now I'm waiting for Foursquare to authorize my developer account. Excited for the developer-friendly API playground offered by Foursquare to us.

title: "while" leetcoding
subtitle: 100 Days of Code - 7
author: CodeWarrior-debug
postBody:
Day 7 - Interesting Leetcode problem today: #278 isBadVersion. Given a list of booleans, after the first false in which the rest of the list are all falses, you are supposed to return the position of the first false with a minimum of calculations.


It requires a 'while' loop instead of the usual 'for' loop (a JS first for me), and currently I'm passing 15/24 testcases before time runs out. Will try again with '-"' and '+=' tomorrow!


28% through Next.js course, have a sweet list of 30 steakhouses populating in my app. Working on this project...keeps me hungry, haha!

subtitle: 100 Days of Code - 13
title: Tailwind - do mobile first!
postBody:
Day 13 - Spent a lot of time working through scaling and media settings - definitely going to practice mobile first development on the next page I build!


Tailwind's default syntax favors mobile first development. The lowest setting is "sm" at 640 pixels wide, larger than typical smartphones.


Also, of the three (or more) ways to hide an element with CSS, Tailwind's decision to use only "display:none" for a hidden choice is appreciated. The other ways lead to confusing DOM behavior.


Okay fine I skipped a few entries but I swear I did the coding, just not the posting...

subtitle: 100 Days of Code - 14
postBody:
Day 14 - Working through having another element appear when another element is hovered over. The challenge is that the design I've been asked to follow doesn't allow a straightforward parent-child or sibling relationship of the two elements.


The solution is likely to translate the lower elements' positions so they can appear next to each other, even though their natural layout would have them further down the page.


CSS can be a puzzle, but satisfying when it's done!
author: CodeWarrior-debug
title: CSS satisfaction

subtitle: 100 Days of Code - 15
postBody:
Day 15 - From yesterday's cutoff, I first tried translating items up. Unfortunately, the space where the original element was remains occupied (just white space) when the element appears, although the element appears above the white space where the element originally was.


React to the rescue (flex on 'em!)


After a lot of wrangling with CSS, the idea occurred to create only one container, but have its values change onMouseEnter & onMouseLeave based on the foreign elements hovered over (useState function in React).


And it works like a charm! Ok, time to enjoy the weekend.

title: Bond, James Bond
postBody:
Day 16 - Work on the client's business site is on pause, so I'm spending some time on a James Bond movie ratings project (using NextJS, Tailwind, and TMDB API).


On the James Bond project, the first filmography page draft has all the Bond Movies showing cards with the basic movie details - next step is building out the page for each individual movie.


An interesting setting to play around with are text overflow settings - whether you want to hide extra text, add an ellipsis, scroll through it, etc. I like to have all information readily at my fingertips, so on hover this lets the user scroll through the full Bond movie overview.

Day 17 - Initial draft of a specific Bond movie page is complete. Clip of "Dr. No" page below!! Nice pictures and shortcuts to a wealth of cinematic detail after a quick film summary so you can see if it's worth a watch.



For some reason Next.js is inconsistent in applying toLocaleString...I will have to use another library to conveniently format dates, numbers, etc. Bizarrely the errors are so serious the page will not even render on localhost during development. 100 Days of Code - 22
postBody:
Day 22 - Breakthrough before lunch, that's my kind of day! What was stopping the project from building in a preview environment? Next.js has several ways to store environment variables: .env.local files using no prefix (for use in development environment only) or with "NEXT_PUBLIC_" prefix (for use in production on the client). But what about the preview versions?



While most tutorials currently don't mention this, the easiest and most fully-featured way to set your environment variables is found on a dedicated page in the settings menu of each Vercel project. https://lnkd.in/dTGBJgZU => that's the location


Just type your environment variables in (you can also import), then pick whether they should apply to Production, Development, and/or Preview. To take it a step further, the preview settings can be customized all the way down to the branch level! Time for tutorials to be updated :)


#100daysofcode #opentowork #frontend #fullstack #nextjs #react #freelance

title: 1k commits and a homepage

postBody:
Day 32-35 - Sent 007-reviews out to a bunch of friends, very grateful for their feedback. Going to delay final launch for a bit and incorporate many of their changes.


In this project I learned or took novice steps in Next.js, Firebase, Tailwindcss, and chartjs (other tools used were far simpler).


 Going forward I would not want to learn more than 2 major tools on a project. Also, it's important to not only learn the tools but to become efficient with them.


So my next project will be a blog in which I focus on mobile-first development and using a state-management library like Recoil. The rest will remain the same stack so coding with those tools becomes quite efficient.

title: wee bit of weebly
postBody:
Day 40 - Working on a client's Weebly site, altering settings clients couldn't change or review through the drag and drop editor.


After removing a Javascript-based conditional selector, I've found that the selector is being cached on the client and so the website experiences only changes after a user clears their web cache. Haven't found a way to force-clear a user's web cache, but will continue to research!
